VALUES
(19, 136, 25, 25, 'kjv', 'Who giveth food to all flesh', 0, 28, 'greek', 'Key Greek Terms', 'The phrase ''giveth food'' translates to δίδωσιν τροφήν (dídōsin trophēn, G1325 and G5160) - ''to give'' and ''food, nourishment.'' This highlights God''s active role in providing sustenance, both physically and spiritually, showing His intention to nurture His creation.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G1325", "description": "Strong''s for ''to give.''"}, {"type": "strongs", "reference": "G5160", "description": "Strong''s for ''food, nourishment.''"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 26, 26, 'kjv', 'O give thanks unto the God of heaven: for his mercy endureth for ever.', 0, 70, 'connection', 'Thankfulness in Scripture', 'This call to give thanks echoes themes found throughout Scripture, notably in 1 Chronicles 16:34, which states, ''O give thanks unto the Lord; for he is good; for his mercy endureth forever.'' Both passages highlight God''s enduring mercy and the importance of gratitude in worship, reminding believers of the continuous call to recognize God''s goodness.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "1 Chronicles 16:34", "description": "Similar exhortation to give thanks for God''s enduring mercy."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 26, 26, 'kjv', 'God of heaven', 23, 36, 'theology', 'Divine Sovereignty', 'Referring to God as the ''God of heaven'' emphasizes His sovereignty and authority over all creation. This title suggests that God not only rules the heavens but also has dominion over the earth. Many scholars believe this reflects the biblical worldview that God''s reign is universal and invites believers to recognize His power in their lives.', 'person.2.fill', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Insight on God''s sovereignty as reflected in this title."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 26, 26, 'kjv', 'for his mercy endureth for ever.', 38, 70, 'greek', 'Understanding Mercy', 'חֶסֶד (chesed, H2617) - mercy, loving-kindness, steadfast love. This Hebrew term encompasses more than mere pity; it signifies a loyal, covenantal love that persists through trials. Recognizing God''s ''chesed'' invites believers to reflect on the profound nature of divine love that is both faithful and enduring.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H2617", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew word for mercy."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 136, 26, 26, 'kjv', 'O give thanks', 0, 13, 'question', 'Personal Gratitude Reflection', 'What specific instances of God''s mercy can I thank Him for today? Reflecting on the personal acts of mercy in our lives can deepen our appreciation for His faithfulness and encourage a spirit of gratitude in our daily walk.', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 137, 1, 1, 'kjv', 'By the rivers of Babylon, there we sat down, yea, we wept, when we remembered Zion.', 0, 83, 'connection', 'Captivity and Mourning', 'Psalm 42:1-2 echoes a similar sentiment of longing for God''s presence, stating, ''As the deer pants for the water brooks, so pants my soul for You, O God. My soul thirsts for God, for the living God.'' This connection highlights the deep emotional and spiritual anguish experienced during exile, emphasizing a profound yearning for restoration and communion with God, akin to the captives'' lament in Babylon.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Psalm 42:1-2", "description": "Reflects a similar longing for God in a time of distress."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 137, 1, 1, 'kjv', 'By the rivers of Babylon, there we sat down, yea, we wept, when we remembered Zion.', 0, 83, 'theology', 'The Nature of Remembrance', 'Many scholars believe this passage illustrates the theological concept of ''remembrance'' as a form of lamentation and hope. In biblical theology, remembering Zion symbolizes not only a physical place but also the covenant relationship between God and His people. This remembrance can invoke both sorrow for loss and a desire for restoration, reflecting the duality of hope and despair in the life of faith.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discusses the significance of Zion and its spiritual implications."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 137, 1, 1, 'kjv', 'when we remembered Zion.', 59, 83, 'greek', 'Concept of ''Remembered''', 'זָכַר (zakar, H2142) - to remember, to mention, to recall. This Hebrew term emphasizes not just the act of memory but also invokes the idea of bringing to mind with intent and significance. In the context of exile, it underscores the captives'' yearning for their homeland and God''s promises associated with Zion.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H2142", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew word for ''remember.''"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 137, 1, 1, 'kjv', 'By the rivers of Babylon, there we sat down, yea, we wept, when we remembered Zion.', 0, 83, 'question', 'Personal Reflection on Exile', 'What does it mean to ''remember Zion'' in your own life? In moments of distress or spiritual exile, how do you recall the promises of God and your identity in Him? Reflecting on this can help deepen your understanding of God''s faithfulness amidst life''s challenges.', 'heart.text.square', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 137, 2, 2, 'kjv', 'We hanged our harps upon the willows in the midst thereof.', 0, 58, 'connection', 'Captivity and Mourning', 'This verse resonates with Lamentations 1:1, which also depicts the sorrow of the Israelites in exile. Both passages reflect the deep emotional and spiritual pain associated with separation from Zion, symbolizing God''s presence. Understanding this connection highlights the themes of loss and longing that permeate the experience of captivity.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Lamentations 1:1", "description": "Lamentations expresses sorrow over Jerusalem''s desolation."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 137, 2, 2, 'kjv', 'hanged our harps', 3, 19, 'greek', 'Significance of ''Hanged''', 'The Hebrew word for ''hanged'' here is תָּלָה (talah, H8518) - to hang, suspend, or to be loosed. This choice of word conveys not just physical action but also a deep emotional state of suspension or abandonment, representing the Israelites'' refusal to engage in joyful worship while in captivity.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H8518", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew word used."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 137, 2, 2, 'kjv', 'our harps upon the willows', 10, 36, 'theology', 'Symbolism of Harps and Willows', 'Many scholars believe that the harps symbolize worship and joy, while the willows represent mourning and desolation. This juxtaposition highlights the tension between the Israelites'' former worship and their current state of despair, illustrating a profound theological truth about worship in times of suffering.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Matthew Henry discusses the symbolism of musical instruments in worship."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 137, 2, 2, 'kjv', 'in the midst thereof.', 37, 58, 'question', 'Presence in Suffering', 'What does it mean to find oneself ''in the midst'' of sorrow and yet still hold onto memories of joy? How can we reconcile our painful circumstances with our identity as worshippers of God?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 137, 3, 3, 'kjv', 'they that carried us away captive', 10, 43, 'connection', 'Exile Themes', 'The phrase resonates with other biblical instances of exile, such as Jeremiah 29:4-7, where God instructs the exiles in Babylon to seek the welfare of the city. This connection emphasizes the enduring pain of captivity alongside God''s call to live faithfully even in difficult circumstances.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Jeremiah 29:4-7", "description": "God''s message to the exiles in Babylon about living faithfully."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 137, 3, 3, 'kjv', 'required of us a song', 44, 65, 'theology', 'Joy Amidst Suffering', 'This verse reflects a theological tension between joy and suffering. Many scholars believe that while the captors demanded joy through song, the reality of exile challenges the notion of praise in hardship. This suggests a deeper understanding of worship as an act of faith, even in despair.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Psalms Commentary by John Gill", "description": "Explains the significance of worship in times of distress."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 137, 3, 3, 'kjv', 'Sing us one of the songs of Zion.', 121, 154, 'question', 'Cultural Identity', 'What does it mean to sing songs of Zion in a foreign land? How does this challenge our understanding of cultural identity and belonging when faced with adversity? Reflecting on this can help us consider how to maintain our faith and identity in challenging circumstances.', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 137, 3, 3, 'kjv', 'that wasted us required of us mirth', 76, 111, 'greek', 'Understanding ''Mirth''', 'מִשְׁתֶּה (mishteh, H4960) - feast, banquet. This word implies not just joy, but a celebratory feast, underscoring the captors’ mockery of the exiled people''s grief. This highlights the deep emotional pain of being forced to perform joy while in sorrow, illustrating the complexity of their situation.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H4960", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew word for ''mirth.''"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 137, 4, 4, 'kjv', 'How shall we sing the Lord’s song in a strange land?', 0, 52, 'connection', 'Cultural Exile Connection', 'This verse reflects the plight of exiles, similar to Jeremiah 29:7, where the Israelites are encouraged to seek the welfare of the city they inhabit. Both passages highlight the challenge of maintaining one''s identity and worship in a foreign context, underscoring the tension between cultural assimilation and spiritual fidelity.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Jeremiah 29:7", "description": "Encourages Israelites to thrive in exile."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 137, 4, 4, 'kjv', 'How shall we sing the Lord’s song in a strange land?', 0, 52, 'theology', 'Worship in Adversity', 'This passage suggests that authentic worship is deeply connected to one''s sense of place and identity. Many scholars believe it illustrates the difficulty of worshiping God when separated from one''s homeland and community, highlighting God''s presence even in exile. It challenges believers to find ways to express faith despite adverse circumstances.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discusses the nature of worship during trials."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 137, 4, 4, 'kjv', 'How shall we sing the Lord’s song in a strange land?', 0, 52, 'question', 'Worship in Foreign Spaces', 'What does it mean to maintain a heart of worship when surrounded by unfamiliarity or opposition? How can we ensure that our songs remain true to the Lord’s message even when we feel disconnected from our spiritual roots?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 137, 4, 4, 'kjv', 'How shall we sing the Lord’s song in a strange land?', 0, 52, 'greek', 'Key Terms in Worship', 'מִזְמוֹר (mizmor, H4210) - a song or poem, often used in worship. This Hebrew term indicates the importance of musical expression in the context of devotion, emphasizing that singing is not merely an act but a deep expression of faith.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H4210", "description": "Indicates the connection between song and worship."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 137, 5, 5, 'kjv', 'If I forget thee, O Jerusalem,', 0, 30, 'connection', 'Connection to Lamentations', 'This phrase echoes sentiments found in Lamentations 3:19-20, where the author laments the memory of Jerusalem amidst suffering. Both texts reflect a deep emotional and spiritual connection to the city, signifying its importance in the Israelite identity and worship. The connection emphasizes the profound grief and longing for Jerusalem''s restoration.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Lamentations 3:19-20", "description": "Similar expressions of grief for Jerusalem."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 137, 5, 5, 'kjv', 'let my right hand forget her cunning.', 31, 68, 'theology', 'Significance of Memory', 'This verse suggests a theological emphasis on memory as integral to identity and worship. Many scholars believe that forgetting Jerusalem is equated with losing one''s ability to serve and create (represented by the ''right hand''). It highlights the importance of remembering God''s promises and covenant, foundational to the Jewish faith.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discusses the significance of remembrance in worship."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 137, 5, 5, 'kjv', 'If I forget thee, O Jerusalem,', 0, 30, 'question', 'Personal Reflection on Memory', 'What does it mean for you to ''remember'' Jerusalem in your spiritual life? How does this call to remembrance influence your relationship with your faith community and your understanding of God''s promises?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 137, 6, 6, 'kjv', 'let my tongue cleave to the roof of my mouth;', 27, 72, 'theology', 'Significance of Speech', 'This phrase highlights the deep connection between memory and identity in the biblical tradition. Many scholars believe it underscores the importance of Jerusalem not just as a physical location but as a symbol of God''s presence and promises. The psalmist expresses that forgetting Jerusalem equates to a loss of voice and purpose, reflecting the theological theme of longing for restoration and divine connection.', 'figure.mind.and.body', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "The New American Commentary on Psalms 137", "description": "Provides insight into the lament and longing for Jerusalem."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 137, 6, 6, 'kjv', 'if I prefer not Jerusalem above my chief joy.', 73, 118, 'connection', 'Joy and Priorities', 'This phrase can be cross-referenced with Matthew 6:21, ''For where your treasure is, there your heart will be also.'' The connection matters as it emphasizes the biblical principle that one''s priorities reflect their true affections. The psalmist''s declaration serves as a reminder of the centrality of spiritual joy in the believer''s life, prompting reflection on what truly brings satisfaction and joy.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Matthew 6:21", "description": "Highlights the relationship between joy and priorities in faith."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 137, 6, 6, 'kjv', 'If I do not remember thee,', 0, 26, 'question', 'Importance of Remembrance', 'What does it mean for us today to remember God in our daily lives? In what ways can we actively keep our focus on Him amidst distractions? This reflection encourages an examination of our practices and habits in maintaining a relationship with God, emphasizing the value of remembrance in our spiritual journey.', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 137, 6, 6, 'kjv', 'let my', 27, 33, 'greek', 'Understanding ''cunning''', 'חָכְמָה (chokmah, H2451) - wisdom, skill, or cunning. This term emphasizes not only intelligence but also the practical application of knowledge. The psalmist''s plea suggests that forgetting Jerusalem equates to losing the very essence of one''s wisdom and skill, highlighting the integral role of divine remembrance in guiding one''s actions.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H2451", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew term used."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 137, 7, 7, 'kjv', 'children of Edom', 22, 38, 'connection', 'Edom''s Role in Scripture', 'The mention of ''children of Edom'' recalls their historical animosity toward Israel, particularly during the Babylonian exile. Notably, Obadiah 1:10-14 condemns Edom for their violence against Israel, further emphasizing God''s judgment on nations that oppose His people. Understanding this context sheds light on the psalmist''s plea for divine remembrance of Edom''s actions.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Obadiah 1:10", "description": "Obadiah condemns Edom for their violence against Israel."}, {"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Lamentations 4:21", "description": "Highlights Edom''s rejoicing over Jerusalem''s destruction."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 137, 7, 7, 'kjv', 'Rase it, rase it', 74, 90, 'theology', 'Destruction and Judgment', 'This phrase, ''Rase it, rase it,'' reflects the intense desire for complete destruction of Jerusalem, illustrating the severity of judgment against sin. Many scholars believe this highlights the theological concept of divine retribution, where nations that act against God''s chosen people face consequences. It serves as a reminder of God''s justice and the seriousness of sin.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discusses the themes of retribution and God''s justice in Psalms."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 137, 7, 7, 'kjv', 'Remember, O Lord', 0, 16, 'question', 'God''s Remembrance', 'What does it mean for God to ''remember'' in the context of His covenant people? How should this understanding influence our prayers and pleas for justice today, particularly in the face of oppression or suffering?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 137, 8, 8, 'kjv', 'O daughter of Babylon, who art to be destroyed;', 0, 47, 'connection', 'Babylon''s Destruction Foretold', 'The phrase ''who art to be destroyed'' echoes the prophetic themes found in Isaiah 47:1-3, where Babylon''s fall is similarly prophesied. This connection emphasizes God''s sovereignty over nations and His judgment against those who oppose His people. Understanding this can deepen one''s appreciation for the justice of God in the face of oppression.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Isaiah 47:1", "description": "Prophecy of Babylon''s downfall"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 137, 8, 8, 'kjv', 'happy shall he be, that rewardeth thee', 48, 86, 'theology', 'Retributive Justice', 'This verse suggests a principle of retributive justice, where God allows vengeance against those who have inflicted suffering. Many scholars believe this serves as a reminder of God''s ultimate justice and the moral order He upholds, reinforcing the idea that while vengeance is not for individuals to seek, God will rectify wrongs in His timing.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Insights on divine justice and retribution"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 137, 8, 8, 'kjv', 'that rewardeth thee as thou hast served us.', 67, 110, 'question', 'Understanding Service and Retribution', 'What does it mean for us to consider how we have served others, especially in the context of suffering? How can this understanding influence our actions and attitudes toward those who have wronged us, considering the principle of divine justice expressed in this verse?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 137, 9, 9, 'kjv', 'Happy shall he be, that taketh and dasheth thy little ones against the stones.', 0, 78, 'connection', 'Connection to Judgment', 'This verse echoes the sentiment found in Psalm 9:12, which states, ''For He who avenges blood remembers; He does not ignore the cries of the afflicted.'' Both passages reflect a theme of divine justice and the consequences of actions against God''s people. This connection emphasizes the seriousness of God''s judgment upon those who perpetrate violence against His chosen ones.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Psalm 9:12", "description": "A related passage emphasizing divine justice."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 137, 9, 9, 'kjv', 'dasheth thy little ones', 35, 58, 'theology', 'The Nature of Wrath', 'Many scholars believe this verse illustrates the depth of God''s wrath against oppressors and highlights the consequences of sin, particularly against innocent lives. This passage serves as a sobering reminder of the severity of God''s judgment and the ultimate fate of those who oppose Him. The imagery of violence reflects the serious nature of sin in a fallen world.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 137, 9, 9, 'kjv', 'Happy shall he be', 0, 17, 'question', 'Understanding True Happiness', 'What does it mean to find happiness in the context of judgment and violence? How does this reflect the biblical understanding of justice and retribution? Reflecting on this phrase challenges us to consider the nature of true happiness as it relates to God''s justice, and whether our understanding aligns with divine principles.', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 137, 9, 9, 'kjv', 'thy little ones against the stones', 43, 77, 'greek', 'Hebrew Insight', 'In the Hebrew text, the phrase for ''little ones'' is ''טָף'' (ṭāph, H2945) - children, infants. This word emphasizes the innocence and vulnerability of the targets of violence, invoking a stronger emotional response to the idea of their harm. The use of this term highlights the gravity of the act described in the verse and God''s concern for the vulnerable.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H2945", "description": "Strong''s number for ''little ones'' in Hebrew."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 138, 1, 1, 'kjv', 'I will praise thee with my whole heart', 0, 38, 'theology', 'Wholehearted Praise', 'This phrase emphasizes the importance of genuine worship, suggesting that God desires not just ritualistic praise but a deep, heartfelt response. Many scholars believe that true worship involves aligning one''s entire being with the act of glorifying God, reflecting both love and commitment. This concept is echoed in Jesus'' teaching in Matthew 22:37, where He cites the command to love God with all one’s heart.', 'person.2.fill', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew 22:37", "description": "Jesus emphasizes the totality of love for God."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 138, 1, 1, 'kjv', 'before the gods will I sing praise unto thee.', 40, 85, 'connection', 'Worship in Context', 'This phrase can be connected to Psalm 96:4-5, where the psalmist declares the greatness of the Lord above all gods. By praising God ''before the gods,'' the psalmist demonstrates a public declaration of faith and contrasts the true God with false idols. This connection highlights the sovereignty of God in a polytheistic world, affirming His supremacy.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Psalm 96:4-5", "description": "Affirmation of God\u2019s supremacy over other deities."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 138, 1, 1, 'kjv', 'I will praise thee with my whole heart', 0, 38, 'question', 'Reflecting on Worship', 'What does it mean to praise God with your whole heart in a world filled with distractions? How can you cultivate a practice of worship that encompasses all aspects of your life?', 'heart.text.square', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 138, 1, 1, 'kjv', 'I will praise thee with my whole heart', 0, 38, 'greek', 'Key Term Analysis', 'כָּל־לֵב (kol-lev, H3605) - whole heart, indicating totality and sincerity in worship. This term signifies not merely the emotions but a complete devotion of mind and spirit in praising God.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H3605", "description": "Strong''s number for ''whole heart''"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 138, 2, 2, 'kjv', 'I will worship toward thy holy temple', 0, 37, 'connection', 'Worship Direction', 'The act of worshiping ''toward thy holy temple'' reflects a tradition seen in other Scriptures, such as 1 Kings 8:44-48, where the temple is a focal point for prayer and worship. This connection emphasizes the importance of a designated place for worship as a means to direct the heart and mind toward God.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "1 Kings 8:44-48", "description": "Describes the temple''s role in prayer and worship."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 138, 2, 2, 'kjv', 'for thy lovingkindness and for thy truth', 59, 99, 'theology', 'Nature of God', 'This phrase highlights God''s attributes of lovingkindness (chesed) and truth (emet), which are foundational to His character. Many scholars believe that these qualities are essential for understanding the covenant relationship between God and His people, emphasizing His faithfulness and mercy.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Psalms Commentary by Derek Kidner", "description": "Explores the significance of God''s attributes in worship."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 138, 2, 2, 'kjv', 'for thou hast magnified thy word above all thy name', 101, 152, 'greek', 'Significance of ''Word''', 'λόγος (logos, G3056) - word, reason, discourse. This term, while primarily Greek, resonates deeply in the Hebrew context, highlighting the importance of God''s promises and decrees. The magnification of His word above His name emphasizes the power and authority of God''s spoken word in establishing truth and reality.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G3056", "description": "Strong''s number for the Greek term ''logos''."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 138, 2, 2, 'kjv', 'I will worship toward thy holy temple', 0, 37, 'question', 'Reflection on Worship', 'What does it mean to you personally to direct your worship toward God''s presence? How can this act of intentional worship shape your understanding of His holiness and your relationship with Him?', 'heart.text.square', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 138, 3, 3, 'kjv', 'In the day when I cried', 0, 23, 'connection', 'Crying Out for Help', 'This phrase echoes the sentiment found in Psalm 34:17, where it states, ''The righteous cry, and the Lord hears, and delivers them out of all their troubles.'' Both passages highlight the assurance that God listens and responds to the cries of His people, reinforcing His role as a compassionate deliverer.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Psalm 34:17", "description": "Similar theme of God hearing the cries of the righteous."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 138, 3, 3, 'kjv', 'strengthenedst me with strength', 48, 79, 'greek', 'Original Language Insight', 'ἰσχύς (ischus, G2479) - strength, might, power. This term emphasizes the idea of divine empowerment, suggesting that God not only answers prayers but actively provides the necessary strength to endure challenges.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G2479", "description": "Strong''s number for the Greek term for strength."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 138, 3, 3, 'kjv', 'thou answeredst me', 24, 42, 'theology', 'God''s Response to Prayer', 'Many scholars believe this verse illustrates the theological concept of God''s responsiveness to prayer. It affirms that prayer is not merely a ritual but a relational dialogue where believers can expect divine engagement and support during their times of need.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Explains God''s willingness to answer the prayers of His people."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 138, 3, 3, 'kjv', 'strength in my soul', 71, 90, 'question', 'Reflection on Inner Strength', 'What does it mean for your soul to be strengthened by God? How can you actively seek this divine strength in your daily life, especially during times of distress or uncertainty?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini');